---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LayerSection from '../components/LayerSection.astro';
import { dbLayers } from '../data/dbLayers.js';
import BTreeSearch from '../components/BTreeSearch.svelte';
import Join from '../components/Join.svelte';
import DbTransaction from '../components/DbTransaction.svelte';
import Isolation from '../components/Isolation.svelte';
import Why from '../components/Why.astro';
import Takeaway from '../components/Takeaway.astro';
import Quiz from '../components/Quiz.svelte';
import PrevNext from '../components/PrevNext.astro';
import SeeAlso from '../components/SeeAlso.astro';
const L = Object.fromEntries(dbLayers.map((l) => [l.id, l]));
const title = 'THE STACK — the database';
const description = 'A deep dive into a database: rows in pages, B-tree indexes, query planning, ACID transactions, the write-ahead log, and replication — how storage becomes reliable answers.';
---
<Base {title} {description} layers={dbLayers}>
  <div slot="hero">
    <div class="kicker">A deep dive into layer 18</div>
    <h1 class="title">THE <em>DATABASE</em><br />STACK</h1>
    <p class="lede">A database is memory that survives questions: rows on disk, indexes that find them fast, transactions that keep them consistent, and copies that keep them alive. Each layer turns raw storage into a reliable answer.</p>
    <div class="hero-meta"><a class="back-link" href="/">← back to the full stack</a> · tables → indexes → queries → joins → transactions → isolation → durability → replication</div>
  </div>

  <LayerSection {...L.D0}>
    <p class="prose">At the bottom a table is just <b>rows</b> packed into fixed-size <span class="hl">pages</span> on disk — a heap of records. Finding one means, by default, reading them all: a full scan.</p>
    <Takeaway>Storage is the easy part; a table is rows in pages, and without help, finding a row means reading every row.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Programs need durable, shared state that outlives a process and survives a crash — more than a file blob."
      idea="Store rows in fixed-size pages the engine can cache and write back efficiently, tracking which page holds what."
      tradeoff="A raw heap is simple but slow to search and easy to fragment; everything above this layer exists to make access fast and safe."
      next="Reading every row to find one doesn't scale — that's what an index fixes."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D1}>
    <p class="prose">An <b>index</b> is a sorted side-structure — usually a <span class="hl">B-tree</span> — that lets the engine descend a few levels to a row instead of scanning the whole table. A million rows become ~20 comparisons.</p>
    <BTreeSearch client:visible />
    <Takeaway>An index trades some write cost and space for lookups that go from O(n) scans to O(log n) tree descents.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="structures" note="the B-tree this index is built on, and how a search descends it" />
    <Why
      problem="Scanning every row to answer a query is fine for ten rows and ruinous for ten million."
      idea="Keep keys in a balanced tree (or hash) so a lookup follows a short path from root to leaf, touching a handful of pages."
      tradeoff="Indexes speed reads but slow writes (every insert updates them) and cost storage, so you index the columns you actually query."
      next="Indexes are tools; the query planner decides when to use them."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D2}>
    <p class="prose">You write <b>what</b> you want — <code>SELECT … WHERE … ORDER BY …</code> — and the <span class="hl">planner</span> decides <b>how</b>: which index to use, whether to scan, in what order to join. Declarative on top, cost-based underneath.</p>
    <Takeaway>SQL says what you want; the planner estimates costs and picks how — index seek vs. scan, join order, sort strategy.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="There are many ways to compute the same result, with wildly different costs, and you don't want to hand-code the fastest one each time."
      idea="Let the query describe the result declaratively, and have a cost-based optimizer use statistics to choose an execution plan."
      tradeoff="Planners are heuristic: bad statistics or unusual queries can pick a terrible plan, which is why EXPLAIN exists."
      next="The planner's hardest call is how to combine two tables — a join."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D3}>
    <p class="prose">Data is split across tables to avoid repeating it (an order stores a <code>user_id</code>, not the whole user). A <b>join</b> stitches them back together where a key matches — <code>users ⋈ orders ON users.id = orders.user_id</code>. The simplest way is a <span class="hl">nested loop</span>: check every left row against every right row.</p>
    <Join client:visible />
    <Takeaway>A join recombines normalized tables on a matching key; an inner join keeps only the rows that pair up — and done naively it costs n×m comparisons.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="structures" note="a hash join builds a hash map on one table so the other just probes it — O(n+m)" />
    <Why
      problem="Normalizing data across tables avoids duplication, but answering real questions means recombining it — and the obvious nested loop is quadratic."
      idea="Match rows on a key. Speed it up with the index from earlier (index-nested-loop: look the key up instead of scanning) or a hash join (build a hash table on one side, probe with the other)."
      tradeoff="Each strategy wins in a different regime — small tables, an indexed key, or one side that fits in memory — which is exactly the call the planner makes."
      next="Reads and joins are half the story — changing data safely is the other half."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D4}>
    <p class="prose">A <b>transaction</b> groups changes so they're <span class="hl">all-or-nothing</span>. Transfer money and crash halfway, and a transaction rolls back to a consistent state — without one, the debit sticks and money vanishes.</p>
    <DbTransaction client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Transactions give you ACID — here, atomicity: the transfer happens completely or not at all, even across a crash.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Real updates touch multiple rows, and a failure partway through can leave the data in an impossible state — money debited but never credited."
      idea="Wrap related changes in a transaction that commits as a unit or rolls back entirely, with isolation so concurrent transactions don't corrupt each other."
      tradeoff="Guarantees cost coordination: locks or versions, log writes, and the classic isolation-vs-throughput tradeoffs."
      next="Atomicity handles crashes — but what about other transactions running at the same time?"
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D5}>
    <p class="prose">Atomicity is the <i>A</i> of ACID; <b>isolation</b> is the <i>I</i>. When transactions run concurrently, one can glimpse another's half-finished work — a <span class="hl">dirty read</span> — or watch a value change underneath it — a <span class="hl">non-repeatable read</span>. The isolation level sets how much interference is allowed; <b>MVCC</b> gives each transaction a stable snapshot.</p>
    <Isolation client:visible />
    <Takeaway>Isolation levels trade safety for speed: weaker levels are faster but let transactions see each other’s mess; a snapshot (MVCC) makes a transaction’s reads stable and consistent.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Many transactions run at once on the same rows, and a naïvely-interleaved read can see uncommitted or shifting data — corrupting decisions made on it."
      idea="Define isolation levels (read uncommitted → committed → repeatable read → serializable) and enforce them, often by keeping multiple row versions so readers get a consistent snapshot (MVCC)."
      tradeoff="Stronger isolation means more locking or version-keeping and less concurrency; serializable is safest but slowest, so most systems default to a weaker level."
      next="Atomic and isolated in memory still isn't enough — a commit has to survive losing power."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D6}>
    <p class="prose">Before changing the data pages, the engine appends the change to a <span class="hl">write-ahead log</span> and flushes that. If the power dies, replaying the log on restart redoes committed work and undoes the rest — so a commit is truly durable.</p>
    <Takeaway>Durability comes from logging the intent first: a committed transaction survives a crash because the log can replay it.</Takeaway>
    <Why
      problem="Writing data pages in place is slow and unsafe — a crash mid-write can corrupt them, and a “committed” change could be lost."
      idea="Append the change to a sequential write-ahead log and fsync it before touching the real pages; on restart, replay the log to recover."
      tradeoff="The log is an extra write on the hot path and must be managed (checkpoints, truncation), but it's what makes commits trustworthy."
      next="One machine can still die entirely — replication keeps a copy alive."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <LayerSection {...L.D7}>
    <p class="prose">A single server is a single point of failure. <b>Replication</b> streams the log to replica machines: reads can spread across them, and if the primary dies, a replica is promoted to take over.</p>
    <Takeaway>Replication copies the database across machines so reads scale and a failure doesn't lose the data — at the cost of consistency tradeoffs.</Takeaway>
    <SeeAlso slug="cloud" note="how this scales reads across a fleet, and the CAP tradeoff it forces" />
    <Why
      problem="If everything lives on one machine, its failure is the database's failure, and all reads contend for it."
      idea="Stream the write-ahead log to replicas that stay in sync; serve reads from them and fail over to one if the primary dies."
      tradeoff="Copies drift: synchronous replication is safe but slow, asynchronous is fast but can lose recent writes — the heart of distributed-database tradeoffs."
      next="Zoom back out: this is what the main stack's Database layer is doing under every cloud app."
    />
  </LayerSection>

  <Quiz slug="database" client:visible />
  <PrevNext slug="database" />
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link{color:var(--accent,var(--signal))}
</style>
